00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:23.290 --> 00:00:24.980
&gt;&gt; Judith Gray: Good afternoon.

00:00:24.980 --> 00:00:26.280
I'm Judith Gray.

00:00:26.280 --> 00:00:29.240 position:56%
I'm the coordinator of reference for
the American Folklife Center here

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:31.180
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:31.180 --> 00:00:34.450
And I'd like to welcome you
to the latest presentation

00:00:34.450 --> 00:00:39.580
in our ongoing series, the Benjamin
A. Botkin Folklife Lecture Series,

00:00:39.580 --> 00:00:43.100
which has been going on since 2003.

00:00:43.100 --> 00:00:46.740
This series allows us to highlight
the work of leading scholars

00:00:46.740 --> 00:00:51.490
in the disciplines of folklore,
ethnomusicology, oral history,

00:00:51.490 --> 00:00:56.390 position:56%
cultural anthropology, and
cultural heritage while specifically

00:00:56.390 --> 00:01:00.550
enhancing the collections here
at the American Folklife Center.

00:01:00.550 --> 00:01:02.490
For the Center and the Library,

00:01:02.490 --> 00:01:05.390
the Botkin lectures
form an important facet

00:01:05.390 --> 00:01:07.890
of our current acquisitions.

00:01:07.890 --> 00:01:10.780
Each lecture is videotaped
and becomes part

00:01:10.780 --> 00:01:13.630
of the permanent collections
of the Center.

00:01:13.630 --> 00:01:17.280
In addition, the lectures
are later posted as webcasts

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:20.890
on the Library's website where
they're available for viewing

00:01:20.890 --> 00:01:23.510
to Internet patrons
throughout the world.

00:01:23.510 --> 00:01:25.620
That being said, let me remind you

00:01:25.620 --> 00:01:28.960
at this point it would be a
good idea to turn off cellphones

00:01:28.960 --> 00:01:32.790
and things that might buzz or
do other interesting things

00:01:32.790 --> 00:01:35.610
to be captured permanently
on the record.

00:01:35.610 --> 00:01:40.220
So today I have the honor
and the distinct pleasure

00:01:40.220 --> 00:01:44.720
of introducing the distinguished
ethnomusicologist Dr. Mark Slobin,

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:46.980
who is the Winslow-Kaplan
Professor of Music

00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:50.320
and American Studies
at Wesleyan University.

00:01:50.320 --> 00:01:54.180
In the course of his career, Dr.
Slobin has written extensively

00:01:54.180 --> 00:01:57.960
on a variety of subjects,
including Eastern European Jewish

00:01:57.960 --> 00:02:00.770
and klezmer music,
global soundtracks,

00:02:00.770 --> 00:02:04.320
and musical subcultures,
ethnomusicological practice

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:07.230
and theory, and the
music of Afghanistan

00:02:07.230 --> 00:02:11.640
where he conducted
research beginning in 1967.

00:02:11.640 --> 00:02:15.500
He has served as the President of
the Society for Ethnomusicology

00:02:15.500 --> 00:02:18.170
and the Society for Asian Music,

00:02:18.170 --> 00:02:22.370
and as Editor of the
journal "Asian Music."

00:02:22.370 --> 00:02:26.170
He's been the recipient of numerous
prizes, including the Seeger Prize

00:02:26.170 --> 00:02:29.630
from the Society for
Ethnomusicology,

00:02:29.630 --> 00:02:34.150
two ASCAP-Deems Taylor
Awards for his books,

00:02:34.150 --> 00:02:37.200
the Jewish Cultural Achievement
Award for Lifetime Achievement

00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:41.090
from the Foundation for Jewish
Culture, and the curt Leviant Award

00:02:41.090 --> 00:02:45.050
in Yiddish Studies from the
Modern Languages Association.

00:02:45.050 --> 00:02:50.160
And in his spare time, during his
45 years as a university professor

00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:53.510
at Wesleyan he has also
trained a significant proportion

00:02:53.510 --> 00:02:58.240
of today's ethnomusicologists, and
I have to say that includes me.

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:02.450
I can only wish all current
graduate students a mentor

00:03:02.450 --> 00:03:06.020
as supportive and as
engaged as Mark.

00:03:06.020 --> 00:03:08.820
Thank you very much.

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:12.630
So next month Mark will
be retiring from Wesleyan

00:03:12.630 --> 00:03:14.040
where he was recently honored

00:03:14.040 --> 00:03:16.610
with a day-long conference
celebrating his career

00:03:16.610 --> 00:03:18.900
and many accomplishments.

00:03:18.900 --> 00:03:21.630
And despite retiring from
full-time teaching though,

00:03:21.630 --> 00:03:24.340
he shows no signs of slowing down.

00:03:24.340 --> 00:03:27.530
And so looking ahead we
hope to see more of him here

00:03:27.530 --> 00:03:31.230
in D.C. He says he hasn't
been invited of late.

00:03:31.230 --> 00:03:35.970
He is now, and especially
to the Library of Congress.

00:03:35.970 --> 00:03:39.210
Today, however, he's going to be
looking backward to discuss some

00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:42.260 position:56%
of his earliest musical experiences.

00:03:42.260 --> 00:03:48.520
And after the lecture he'll be
available for a book signing,

00:03:48.520 --> 00:03:51.610
"Folk Music, A Very
Short Introduction,"

00:03:51.610 --> 00:03:56.540
which will be available for sale
and for his signature right after.

00:03:56.540 --> 00:04:00.960 position:56%
So for the moment, please join me in
welcoming Mark Slobin for his talk

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:07.510
on Improvising Musical Metropolis,
Detroit, 1940s to the 1960s.

00:04:07.510 --> 00:04:13.040
[ Applause ]

00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:18.700
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: Thanks, it's great
to be here in these hallowed halls.

00:04:18.700 --> 00:04:21.980 position:56%
And as you've heard, I've worked on
many things over a very long career.

00:04:21.980 --> 00:04:24.980
And for some reason
because Detroit was so much

00:04:24.980 --> 00:04:27.500
in the news I kept
explaining it to people.

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:30.100
And I said, "Well," I said,
"Nobody understands this place."

00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:33.260
I grew up there, and what would it
be like to study it a little bit

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:37.210
and see what the music culture was
really like in the city in my day?

00:04:37.210 --> 00:04:38.840
So this is a curious project

00:04:38.840 --> 00:04:41.750
because it's partly a
memoir, but it's not a memoir.

00:04:41.750 --> 00:04:45.570
It's also a study of this
city -- the life of a city.

00:04:45.570 --> 00:04:47.550
There is no book that is the life

00:04:47.550 --> 00:04:51.330
of an American city's music
in any period of time.

00:04:51.330 --> 00:04:52.930
We just don't do that.

00:04:52.930 --> 00:04:55.170
So it's an interesting project.

00:04:55.170 --> 00:04:57.840
So I'm going to give you a
certain update on what I'm up to.

00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:03.410
And I'm writing the book
now that will be based on.

00:05:03.410 --> 00:05:05.400
What you find out when you
work on so many projects is

00:05:05.400 --> 00:05:07.850
that your mind always
goes the same direction.

00:05:07.850 --> 00:05:11.430
So I've always been interested
in small musical systems

00:05:11.430 --> 00:05:13.720
that are embedded within
a larger system,

00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:15.510
of many kinds of things going on,

00:05:15.510 --> 00:05:18.810
and some overarching musical
structure in a society,

00:05:18.810 --> 00:05:20.520
of what I've called micromusic.

00:05:20.520 --> 00:05:23.690
So I began to realize
looking at Detroit I was --

00:05:23.690 --> 00:05:26.000
it was really kind of
a micromusic study.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.950
So I'm going to be explaining that.

00:05:29.950 --> 00:05:33.200
And cities are extremely
complicated.

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:38.000 position:56%
One of the great thinkers on cities,
Henri Lefebvre, French theorist,

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:43.510
says that, "The city unveils
a number of systems hidden

00:05:43.510 --> 00:05:45.830
in the illusion of oneness.

00:05:45.830 --> 00:05:49.720
And the city manifests
itself as a group of groups,

00:05:49.720 --> 00:05:55.280
which is a situation of plurality,
coexistence, and simultaneity."

00:05:55.280 --> 00:05:57.030
These are what I've
found in the music.

00:05:57.030 --> 00:05:58.520
There's a very complex system

00:05:58.520 --> 00:06:00.620
of interactive parts
in this great city.

00:06:00.620 --> 00:06:03.230
So the talk is in four parts.

00:06:03.230 --> 00:06:07.130
First I'll frame Detroit as
a city in my day and myself

00:06:07.130 --> 00:06:09.910
as an actor -- as a person there.

00:06:09.910 --> 00:06:11.680 position:56%
Then I'll talk about this mainstream

00:06:11.680 --> 00:06:15.100
of micromusical interactivity
within the city.

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:17.050
I've used the word
superculture in my writings

00:06:17.050 --> 00:06:21.960
for this overarching structure
that one has, and then subcultures.

00:06:21.960 --> 00:06:27.140
Then I'll look at some of the
micromusical systems themselves,

00:06:27.140 --> 00:06:29.650
including my own community,
the Jewish community.

00:06:29.650 --> 00:06:31.540
And then I'll talk
about some directions

00:06:31.540 --> 00:06:37.120
for understanding musical --
urban musical spatiality, okay.

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:39.190
So first, what is Detroit?

00:06:39.190 --> 00:06:40.650
What was it then?

00:06:40.650 --> 00:06:44.630
Detroit grew later and more
explosively than other --

00:06:44.630 --> 00:06:48.640
more than industrial cities
like Chicago and Cleveland.

00:06:48.640 --> 00:06:52.840
It outgrew its modest status as
a kind of waterways crossroads

00:06:52.840 --> 00:06:58.660 position:56%
and site of small manufacturing,
ovens, typewriters, only after 1910.

00:06:58.660 --> 00:07:00.460
Doubled in size by 1920.

00:07:00.460 --> 00:07:02.130
Doubled again by 1930.

00:07:02.130 --> 00:07:05.870
So it's a very late,
very explosive growth.

00:07:05.870 --> 00:07:10.630
And it owes it simply to one
factor, the success of Henry Ford

00:07:10.630 --> 00:07:14.700
and his rivals in attracting
a huge proletarian workforce

00:07:14.700 --> 00:07:17.010
to create a mass market
for the automobile.

00:07:17.010 --> 00:07:20.470
Detroit has been called the
capital of the 20th century

00:07:20.470 --> 00:07:23.120
because of the way it
defined modern production

00:07:23.120 --> 00:07:25.330
and modern industrial life.

00:07:25.330 --> 00:07:28.700
And somebody says it was in
a state of continuous flux

00:07:28.700 --> 00:07:32.040
with as few stagnant moments
and interruptions as possible.

00:07:32.040 --> 00:07:34.340
So this is a very dynamic
system I'm looking at,

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:37.170
not some kind of frozen,
industrial city.

00:07:37.170 --> 00:07:39.970
Both the corporate systems
and the governmental systems,

00:07:39.970 --> 00:07:43.830
part of this superculture, had to
improvise -- that's my title --

00:07:43.830 --> 00:07:47.880
continuously and drastically by
the conditions that they created.

00:07:47.880 --> 00:07:49.410
The invention of the automobile

00:07:49.410 --> 00:07:52.400
and people using it itself
changed the conditions of life.

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:56.820
The scale of building was
unprecedented, actually.

00:07:56.820 --> 00:07:59.410
And eventually we get
the first urban freeway

00:07:59.410 --> 00:08:01.020
and the first shopping
center in America.

00:08:01.020 --> 00:08:06.670
And by the 1950s the twin
logics of capitalism and racism,

00:08:06.670 --> 00:08:07.970
combined with arrogance

00:08:07.970 --> 00:08:11.940
and short-sightedness destroyed
Detroit's economic base,

00:08:11.940 --> 00:08:15.050
making it the only American
city to both rise above

00:08:15.050 --> 00:08:16.910
and fall below a million
inhabitants.

00:08:16.910 --> 00:08:18.750
Okay, the demographic key

00:08:18.750 --> 00:08:22.720
to the city was the accelerated
arrival of three supergroups.

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:24.190
Internally they were very diverse,

00:08:24.190 --> 00:08:26.370
but musically they
look kind of cohesive.

00:08:26.370 --> 00:08:30.060
First, the European immigrants such
as my relatives, until the cutoff

00:08:30.060 --> 00:08:32.440
of mass immigration in 1924.

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:37.540
Second -- the largest were 350,000
Polish Americans in this city

00:08:37.540 --> 00:08:41.540
that got up to about 2 million.

00:08:41.540 --> 00:08:45.290
Second, African Americans from
the South who appeared later

00:08:45.290 --> 00:08:47.760
and more intensively to
Detroit than other cities

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:49.500
as part of the Great Migration.

00:08:49.500 --> 00:08:52.530
And third, white Southerners
who streamed in by the hundreds

00:08:52.530 --> 00:08:54.810
of thousands, particularly
during the war years

00:08:54.810 --> 00:08:57.740
when the population
explodes yet again.

00:08:57.740 --> 00:09:00.220
These supercultures --
these subcultures, I say,

00:09:00.220 --> 00:09:03.710
were also improvising, finding
ways to survive the rigors

00:09:03.710 --> 00:09:06.080
of the workplace, manage
their communities,

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:09.000
create an expressive culture,
especially including music,

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.140 position:56%
and get along with other immigrants.

00:09:11.140 --> 00:09:14.100
Detroit was a pressure cooker, and
the heat was turned on too high.

00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:16.820
It exploded in the
great wartime race riot

00:09:16.820 --> 00:09:20.670
of 1943, just after I was born.

00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:22.780
This was the only American
city to be occupied

00:09:22.780 --> 00:09:25.610
by the U.S. Army three times.

00:09:25.610 --> 00:09:31.020
I was just three months old
and spent the day -- maybe --

00:09:31.020 --> 00:09:33.410
could we -- do you think
the front lights go down?

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:34.710
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:09:34.710 --> 00:09:36.010
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: It will
be interesting to see

00:09:36.010 --> 00:09:37.860
if the front lights go down.

00:09:37.860 --> 00:09:40.210
There I am just before the riot.

00:09:40.210 --> 00:09:44.580 position:56%
And we were in Belle Isle, this
beautiful island park of Belle Isle.

00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:45.880
How did I get to be there?

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:48.520
My father was born in Detroit,

00:09:48.520 --> 00:09:51.050
and his mother was born
in New York in 1890.

00:09:51.050 --> 00:09:53.890
So on that side I'm
third-generation American-born.

00:09:53.890 --> 00:09:56.580
But everybody else came
from Southern Ukraine.

00:09:56.580 --> 00:10:00.760
A few family photos will show
the pathway to America and a kind

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:04.360 position:56%
of assimilation in how I became kind

00:10:04.360 --> 00:10:07.370
of a mixed subcultural
and mainstream person.

00:10:07.370 --> 00:10:11.010
So I'll just run through
a few photos here.

00:10:11.010 --> 00:10:13.870
This is my father's parents
having their honeymoon.

00:10:13.870 --> 00:10:18.340
If you were immigrants in
1910 you go to Niagara Falls

00:10:18.340 --> 00:10:21.820
for your honeymoon, even
if it looks like that.

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:25.400
And you see the industrial
smoke from the Nabisco factory,

00:10:25.400 --> 00:10:28.070
and what it means to
be an immigrant.

00:10:28.070 --> 00:10:29.370
She was only 19 there.

00:10:29.370 --> 00:10:32.160
She looks a great deal older.

00:10:32.160 --> 00:10:34.530 position:56%
And here is the -- my mother's side.

00:10:34.530 --> 00:10:37.110
That's my mother, the
little girl, in Ukraine.

00:10:37.110 --> 00:10:41.740
At the same time, right in the
same -- just a couple years later.

00:10:41.740 --> 00:10:45.200
And she got to America.

00:10:45.200 --> 00:10:50.820
And then my parents' honeymoon is
of course, they're Americans now.

00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:55.200
And they go see New York and
go to the Statue of Liberty.

00:10:55.200 --> 00:10:57.400
Okay, and then there's my growing

00:10:57.400 --> 00:11:02.150
up as an American-slash-subcultural
person.

00:11:02.150 --> 00:11:04.060
So what does this mean?

00:11:04.060 --> 00:11:06.480
It means cowboys and Indians.

00:11:06.480 --> 00:11:09.240
Okay, so here I am
wearing my cowboy thing,

00:11:09.240 --> 00:11:11.490
and there's my little friend
David Droffler [assumed spelling]

00:11:11.490 --> 00:11:13.550
with his headdress.

00:11:13.550 --> 00:11:15.940
Okay, this is what it
means to be American, okay,

00:11:15.940 --> 00:11:20.450
is to be bouncing off
subcultural issues.

00:11:20.450 --> 00:11:25.260
Here I am as a mainstream
person, okay.

00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:27.380
This is -- and my mother
is just great.

00:11:27.380 --> 00:11:29.750
She wrote, "Superman,
1946," you know,

00:11:29.750 --> 00:11:32.000
so I know exactly what
these things are.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.590
So here -- so that's
also mainstream, okay,

00:11:35.590 --> 00:11:38.210
popular culture is mainstream.

00:11:38.210 --> 00:11:39.900
And then we went to Mexico,

00:11:39.900 --> 00:11:43.760
so then I get to be a gringo
and an American tourist.

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:47.840
Okay, all coming out of this
immigrant kind of roots.

00:11:47.840 --> 00:11:49.280
But this is what America means.

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:52.490
It's a set of stereotypes
and activities that relate

00:11:52.490 --> 00:11:57.720
to popular culture
and so forth, okay.

00:11:57.720 --> 00:12:03.160
Okay, so all right,
we'll go back here.

00:12:03.160 --> 00:12:05.370
Right, so I left the
Detroit area for --

00:12:05.370 --> 00:12:09.160
from nearby Ann Arbor where I got
my doctorate after I was in --

00:12:09.160 --> 00:12:11.110
I went off to do Afghanistan.

00:12:11.110 --> 00:12:14.790
It was just at the same
time as the -- another riot.

00:12:14.790 --> 00:12:17.850
So I'm kind of framed by these
rebellions, or uprisings,

00:12:17.850 --> 00:12:21.920
or whatever they're
called in 1943 and 1967.

00:12:21.920 --> 00:12:25.470
Detroit has barely survived
the aftershocks and the decline

00:12:25.470 --> 00:12:28.170
of these various explosions,
trying literally, actually,

00:12:28.170 --> 00:12:30.020
to crawl out of the rubble,

00:12:30.020 --> 00:12:33.640
even as the unconcerned suburbs
thrive very well in the area.

00:12:33.640 --> 00:12:37.590
It's very hard for me to map
my city onto what I see today,

00:12:37.590 --> 00:12:39.110
but that's another story.

00:12:39.110 --> 00:12:41.140
Okay, so we'll get to part two now,

00:12:41.140 --> 00:12:44.120
the life of music in
this metropolis.

00:12:44.120 --> 00:12:46.900
And here I'm concentrating on
what I've called the superculture,

00:12:46.900 --> 00:12:50.250
which in this case is
the educational system --

00:12:50.250 --> 00:12:52.630
music education.

00:12:52.630 --> 00:12:55.250
Detroit's combination
of dynamic growth

00:12:55.250 --> 00:12:58.400
and tense social negotiation
was nowhere more apparent

00:12:58.400 --> 00:13:03.160
than in the designed space -- and
Lefebvre talks about designed space

00:13:03.160 --> 00:13:06.660
and lived space -- but public
schools are part of designed space.

00:13:06.660 --> 00:13:10.380
High school music showcases the
stability and the turbulence

00:13:10.380 --> 00:13:12.090
of a rapidly-changing city.

00:13:12.090 --> 00:13:14.030 position:56%
I'm going to single out two schools.

00:13:14.030 --> 00:13:16.680
One is Miller High
where my father taught.

00:13:16.680 --> 00:13:20.020
He was a school teacher in 1937.

00:13:20.020 --> 00:13:22.840
And Cass Tech, my alma mater,

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:26.460
and that of countless important
musicians from Ron Carter

00:13:26.460 --> 00:13:29.660
and Diana Ross, through
Geri Allen and Jack White.

00:13:29.660 --> 00:13:32.180
All these people went
to Cass Tech, okay.

00:13:32.180 --> 00:13:34.100
Its music program is extraordinary.

00:13:34.100 --> 00:13:36.800
So the overlap and the
distinctions between Miller High

00:13:36.800 --> 00:13:40.060
and Cass Tech give me a really
nice platform for talking

00:13:40.060 --> 00:13:42.140
about a lot of musical issues.

00:13:42.140 --> 00:13:44.570
And I have some first-hand
experience as well.

00:13:44.570 --> 00:13:49.270 position:56%
So actually you can look at American
literature on public school music.

00:13:49.270 --> 00:13:53.420
In 1941, "The WPA Guide
to Michigan" said,

00:13:53.420 --> 00:13:56.790
"Pioneer work in public school
music has been important

00:13:56.790 --> 00:13:58.250
to the entire nation."

00:13:58.250 --> 00:14:01.150
And then in 1940 a book called,

00:14:01.150 --> 00:14:05.040
"High School Music" presents Cass
Tech's curriculum in the survey

00:14:05.040 --> 00:14:06.990
of renowned programs in America.

00:14:06.990 --> 00:14:11.020
And here is the ideology,
"Nothing is more significant

00:14:11.020 --> 00:14:15.280
of the increasing socialization of
education than the rapid extinction

00:14:15.280 --> 00:14:20.170
of instrumental study in
connection with schools.

00:14:20.170 --> 00:14:23.570
Playing upon an instrument is not
merely a personal accomplishment

00:14:23.570 --> 00:14:26.380
with individual benefits,
but is a social power

00:14:26.380 --> 00:14:29.860
which affects many persons in
addition to the performer."

00:14:29.860 --> 00:14:31.340
So this is very strong ideology

00:14:31.340 --> 00:14:33.770
about the importance
of instrumental music.

00:14:33.770 --> 00:14:37.630
At Miller High, this attractive
version of Americanization

00:14:37.630 --> 00:14:40.960 position:56%
through music was largely foreclosed
by the Board of Education.

00:14:40.960 --> 00:14:44.460
Miller had been a junior high,
was changed to senior in 1933

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:47.460
to accommodate the huge influx
of African American students.

00:14:47.460 --> 00:14:49.050
The white parents were notified.

00:14:49.050 --> 00:14:51.450
They could move their
children out of the district.

00:14:51.450 --> 00:14:53.700
So the school quickly
became all black.

00:14:53.700 --> 00:14:55.840
This impacted the music.

00:14:55.840 --> 00:14:58.770
There's a wonderful interview
I found in a dissertation

00:14:58.770 --> 00:15:02.320
with a music teacher who would have
been a colleague of my father's,

00:15:02.320 --> 00:15:03.620
Ms. Dolman [assumed spelling].

00:15:03.620 --> 00:15:08.140
"In 1940," she says, "the
Board removed all the classical

00:15:08.140 --> 00:15:09.440
instruments from Miller,

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:12.260
sending them to other schools
whose students' background

00:15:12.260 --> 00:15:17.900
and breeding would lend them better
to cultured classical music."

00:15:17.900 --> 00:15:22.120
So if you wonder why Milt
Jackson played the vibes instead

00:15:22.120 --> 00:15:26.600
of the cello, this might
be -- he went to Miller.

00:15:26.600 --> 00:15:29.820
There -- you know, there are
some really precise things here.

00:15:29.820 --> 00:15:32.950
Things didn't work out that way due
to the dedication of the teachers

00:15:32.950 --> 00:15:36.440
who struggled and succeed in
supporting all these amazing kids

00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:37.740
who were coming through Miller.

00:15:37.740 --> 00:15:40.360
"High School Music" says,
"The aim of instrumental study

00:15:40.360 --> 00:15:43.950
in schools is principally cultural
and social, and only incidentally

00:15:43.950 --> 00:15:45.940
and remotely vocational."

00:15:45.940 --> 00:15:48.250
Okay, but Ms. Dolman
says something else.

00:15:48.250 --> 00:15:51.930
She says, "Music classes were
business classes for our kids.

00:15:51.930 --> 00:15:54.730
They practiced long and hard
to develop their skills,

00:15:54.730 --> 00:15:57.330
and that's why Kenneth
Burrell and William Evans" --

00:15:57.330 --> 00:15:58.750
later Yusef Lateef --

00:15:58.750 --> 00:16:01.360
"Milton Jackson, and
several others are recognized

00:16:01.360 --> 00:16:03.290
as being the best at
their instruments."

00:16:03.290 --> 00:16:06.090
I can't help mentioning my father
actually taught American History

00:16:06.090 --> 00:16:10.120
to Kenny Burrell, and probably
many other future Jazz greats,

00:16:10.120 --> 00:16:12.030
when he was in Miller.

00:16:12.030 --> 00:16:16.610
"Milt Jackson in his dissertation
notes that had he not dropped

00:16:16.610 --> 00:16:18.910
out of high school he probably
would have gotten a college music

00:16:18.910 --> 00:16:21.560
scholarship like a lot
of his classmates did."

00:16:21.560 --> 00:16:26.640
Dolman's eyewitness account is in
this remarkable 1970 dissertation

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:30.440
by [inaudible] Jones, and they
opposed the establishment.

00:16:30.440 --> 00:16:33.720
"High School Music" again
says, "America does not have

00:16:33.720 --> 00:16:36.340
that racial solidarity
which favors the development

00:16:36.340 --> 00:16:38.140
of peculiar musical idioms.

00:16:38.140 --> 00:16:40.760
While we've discovered interesting
folk music among the Indians

00:16:40.760 --> 00:16:44.550
and Negroes and make use of it and
enjoy it, yet it cannot be said

00:16:44.550 --> 00:16:49.470 position:56%
that this is typical of the American
people at any period [laughter]."

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:53.410 position:56%
Now Ms. Dolman's response of this
erasure of subcultural tradition was

00:16:53.410 --> 00:16:56.650
to help build a model for
success in establishment music.

00:16:56.650 --> 00:17:00.500 position:56%
She tells us that the African
American students couldn't get buses

00:17:00.500 --> 00:17:04.020
to go to the competitions,
but they went anyway,

00:17:04.020 --> 00:17:06.890
and they would win the
all-city band contests.

00:17:06.890 --> 00:17:10.130
"They could read and play all
types of music, even the Mozart

00:17:10.130 --> 00:17:12.560
that the bigshots downtown
felt was not akin

00:17:12.560 --> 00:17:15.670
to their heritage," she says.

00:17:15.670 --> 00:17:17.780
Dolman -- oh, wait.

00:17:17.780 --> 00:17:21.240
I have a picture of this
which I'm not showing you.

00:17:21.240 --> 00:17:24.050
Okay, so here's Miller High.

00:17:24.050 --> 00:17:28.440
And up in Fine Arts here,
Fine Arts, we have --

00:17:28.440 --> 00:17:31.910
woops, get this -- Ms. Dolman here.

00:17:31.910 --> 00:17:36.420
And then under Social Studies
we have my father here, okay.

00:17:36.420 --> 00:17:37.740
So -- and his friends.

00:17:37.740 --> 00:17:42.240
These were all people who came
over to our house all the time.

00:17:42.240 --> 00:17:45.950
The -- this huge mass of Jewish
school teachers in Detroit.

00:17:45.950 --> 00:17:52.500
Dolman also made use of black
resources right in the building.

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:54.960
She brought in a janitor
to help train her chorus.

00:17:54.960 --> 00:17:56.260
And I presume this is somebody

00:17:56.260 --> 00:17:59.260
who probably had church gospel
singing background, or was helpful

00:17:59.260 --> 00:18:00.870
with her training courses.

00:18:00.870 --> 00:18:03.960
I site her because we
have her testimony.

00:18:03.960 --> 00:18:08.190
She's not famous like the great
Luis Cabrera who Yusef Lateef

00:18:08.190 --> 00:18:10.500
and Kenny Burrell site
as really important

00:18:10.500 --> 00:18:12.880
in their musical formation, who
was also teaching at Cass Tech.

00:18:12.880 --> 00:18:15.640
And I'll bring Cabrera back later.

00:18:15.640 --> 00:18:21.170
The supportive music of Miller
High, which only lasts until 1957,

00:18:21.170 --> 00:18:24.100
offers a striking compliment
to the general urban trajectory

00:18:24.100 --> 00:18:26.740
of Detroit marked by black
neighborhood destruction

00:18:26.740 --> 00:18:28.870
for freeways to the
newly-built suburbs,

00:18:28.870 --> 00:18:31.810
relocation of housing
projects, and a combination

00:18:31.810 --> 00:18:35.680
of heavy-handed policing
and economic neglect.

00:18:35.680 --> 00:18:39.330
So music shows us that the
superculture systems, however,

00:18:39.330 --> 00:18:42.390
are not hegemonic wholes,
but they're partial systems

00:18:42.390 --> 00:18:44.830 position:56%
with cracks that offer alternatives.

00:18:44.830 --> 00:18:47.710
We should not forget the musical
families like the McKinneys

00:18:47.710 --> 00:18:50.570
of Detroit and the Joneses --
and we're talking Thad Jones,

00:18:50.570 --> 00:18:54.600
Elvin Jones, that family -- that
nurtured talent outside of school.

00:18:54.600 --> 00:18:57.980
The pianist Barry Harris
who was himself to this day,

00:18:57.980 --> 00:19:00.660
in his late 80s, an
influential teacher,

00:19:00.660 --> 00:19:04.520
as a teenager taught all
the other kids stuff.

00:19:04.520 --> 00:19:06.790
And I asked him, I said,
"What about what you learned

00:19:06.790 --> 00:19:08.610
at school in what you learned?"

00:19:08.610 --> 00:19:11.930
And he said, "Outside,"
he said, "well,

00:19:11.930 --> 00:19:14.250
at school we just learned
stock arrangements."

00:19:14.250 --> 00:19:17.460
But as street musicians he
says they picked up the skills

00:19:17.460 --> 00:19:19.200
in the neighborhood and
among these families.

00:19:19.200 --> 00:19:21.250
So you have a very complicated kind

00:19:21.250 --> 00:19:24.250
of superculture/subculture
relationship going on.

00:19:24.250 --> 00:19:27.210
Cass Tech offers a
different model of patronage.

00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:30.160
It was the magnet school for
the entire city of Detroit.

00:19:30.160 --> 00:19:32.350
There was one gigantic
magnet school.

00:19:32.350 --> 00:19:37.050
It was eight stories high,
occupied a huge downtown space.

00:19:37.050 --> 00:19:40.070
And it wanted to let kids advance

00:19:40.070 --> 00:19:42.310
from every subculture
simultaneously.

00:19:42.310 --> 00:19:46.180
By 1926 business leaders
could praise Cass

00:19:46.180 --> 00:19:49.670
as "A monumental achievement
of education and architecture

00:19:49.670 --> 00:19:51.410
of which any city would be proud."

00:19:51.410 --> 00:19:54.700
This included those art programs
that are in high school music.

00:19:54.700 --> 00:19:59.900
And Cass Tech's own literature
says that they "placed students

00:19:59.900 --> 00:20:03.530
in enviable positions
in symphony orchestras,

00:20:03.530 --> 00:20:06.240
concert bands, radio
and dance bands."

00:20:06.240 --> 00:20:07.910
So this is teens, '20s, '30s.

00:20:07.910 --> 00:20:11.510
As those positions dried
up in the post-war period,

00:20:11.510 --> 00:20:14.880
the emphasis shifted to preparing
students to be music teachers,

00:20:14.880 --> 00:20:18.160
creating a very constructive
cycle of educational continuity

00:20:18.160 --> 00:20:19.580
that I've been looking at.

00:20:19.580 --> 00:20:21.360
Cass Tech's alums readily

00:20:21.360 --> 00:20:24.010
and universally praise the
school's music training.

00:20:24.010 --> 00:20:27.370
They, quote, "are affectionate
and loyal to Detroit."

00:20:27.370 --> 00:20:29.700
Now one doesn't think Detroit's
a place people are affectionate

00:20:29.700 --> 00:20:31.000
and loyal by [laughter].

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:33.080
It's supposed to be this gritty
city we barely escaped from.

00:20:33.080 --> 00:20:37.580
But when you look in music you
get a different storyline, right?

00:20:37.580 --> 00:20:41.750
And alongside African American
students, the white students

00:20:41.750 --> 00:20:44.090
at Cass Tech were on a jazz trek.

00:20:44.090 --> 00:20:47.080
They were recruited straight out
of the classroom in the early '40s,

00:20:47.080 --> 00:20:49.780
so the Tommy Dorsey
and Sam Kenton bands.

00:20:49.780 --> 00:20:52.170
Some of these kids
were Polish Americans,

00:20:52.170 --> 00:20:54.600
and some went on to
fuel the engine of polka

00:20:54.600 --> 00:20:58.410
that energized their huge
population, which I'll get to.

00:20:58.410 --> 00:20:59.740
There's a great history of all this

00:20:59.740 --> 00:21:02.430
by a woman named Lori Gomulka
whose father was a big-time

00:21:02.430 --> 00:21:03.730
polka musician.

00:21:03.730 --> 00:21:06.210
She quotes this one band leader,
Stan Visniok [assumed spelling],

00:21:06.210 --> 00:21:10.180
about Cass Tech, "When I
heard that concert band,

00:21:10.180 --> 00:21:12.300
tears just rolled down my eyes.

00:21:12.300 --> 00:21:13.920 position:56%
Boy, I'm going to be a part of this.

00:21:13.920 --> 00:21:16.150
It just warmed my heart."

00:21:16.150 --> 00:21:19.000
Apparently the students would
skip school to hear Tommy Dorsey

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:20.730
at the nearby Fox Theater.

00:21:20.730 --> 00:21:24.510
The music teachers would also turn
up, and take attendance, and stay.

00:21:24.510 --> 00:21:29.070
[ Laughter ]

00:21:29.070 --> 00:21:30.790
So this is serious music training.

00:21:30.790 --> 00:21:34.240
And then, you know, some of
these kids we would hire.

00:21:34.240 --> 00:21:37.720
So they could move out to New
York or people could move back

00:21:37.720 --> 00:21:39.540
to their home neighborhoods
out of this.

00:21:39.540 --> 00:21:41.410
They were both kind of
viable career options

00:21:41.410 --> 00:21:43.740
that Cass Tech made available.

00:21:43.740 --> 00:21:47.940
African Americans really
benefitted from this rigorous

00:21:47.940 --> 00:21:49.340
yet open-minded curriculum.

00:21:49.340 --> 00:21:53.110
Ron Carter -- Ronald Carter,
I have him on the programs,

00:21:53.110 --> 00:21:54.540
trained in classical chamber music.

00:21:54.540 --> 00:21:56.240
I know people who played
string quartets with him

00:21:56.240 --> 00:21:58.100
on the cello at Cass Tech.

00:21:58.100 --> 00:22:01.240
And this carried on through
the work of Marcus Belgrave

00:22:01.240 --> 00:22:06.420
who was brought late in the
game, and who taught Geri Allen.

00:22:06.420 --> 00:22:09.460
Geri Allen's most recent album,
"Grand River Crossing" is

00:22:09.460 --> 00:22:13.740
about crossing this huge street
in Detroit that I know very well.

00:22:13.740 --> 00:22:17.830 position:56%
She says in her album, "At Cass
Tech we didn't just have a few music

00:22:17.830 --> 00:22:19.780
classes, we had three
years of intensive training

00:22:19.780 --> 00:22:23.700
by master teachers, the Detroit
Artist-in-Residence, for the fields

00:22:23.700 --> 00:22:27.360
of the classics, old and modern
jazz, spirituals, and the blues."

00:22:27.360 --> 00:22:29.510
So note the blending of
the kind of superculture

00:22:29.510 --> 00:22:32.380
and subcultural musics within this.

00:22:32.380 --> 00:22:35.000
Regina Carter is another
Belgrave student.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:38.280
She combines her subcultural
heritage and school training

00:22:38.280 --> 00:22:40.310
on her recent album
"Southern Comfort."

00:22:40.310 --> 00:22:42.230
She's really interesting.

00:22:42.230 --> 00:22:44.810
She has pieces that are
written around memories

00:22:44.810 --> 00:22:46.890
of her childhood trips
back to Alabama

00:22:46.890 --> 00:22:48.810
from Detroit on family visits.

00:22:48.810 --> 00:22:52.060
And she uses '30 field
recordings from nearby

00:22:52.060 --> 00:22:56.180
to where we are sitting
in the recording.

00:22:56.180 --> 00:22:59.890
So she's combining her Cass Tech
technical, classical training

00:22:59.890 --> 00:23:03.050
with the sounds of the
cotton field in this kind

00:23:03.050 --> 00:23:06.060
of very interesting way,
which is a very Detroit story.

00:23:06.060 --> 00:23:09.040
For other types of
subcultural students who --

00:23:09.040 --> 00:23:12.320
you had to qualify to get to Cass
Tech -- the white Southerners,

00:23:12.320 --> 00:23:15.310
the Jews, Italians,
Armenians, Greeks, Serbs,

00:23:15.310 --> 00:23:17.230
etcetera, etcetera, etcetera.

00:23:17.230 --> 00:23:18.530
The grounding in theory

00:23:18.530 --> 00:23:21.730
and the ensembles became a
gateway to different careers.

00:23:21.730 --> 00:23:25.270
One of my orchestra-mates was
the cornetist Hachig Kazarian,

00:23:25.270 --> 00:23:30.780
who is an absolute icon of Armenian
American music for 50 years.

00:23:30.780 --> 00:23:33.730 position:56%
He said he learned more about
mainstream music at Cass than he did

00:23:33.730 --> 00:23:36.850
at Julliard, which
he dropped out of.

00:23:36.850 --> 00:23:38.840
He got on this track
by going directly

00:23:38.840 --> 00:23:41.910
from school to jobs at ethnic bars.

00:23:41.910 --> 00:23:46.210
Another guy in the orchestra,
before my time, Rodney Glusac,

00:23:46.210 --> 00:23:50.560
said he started a Serbian band
with two classmates in 1951,

00:23:50.560 --> 00:23:54.330
and they broke up in
2009 [laughter].

00:23:54.330 --> 00:23:57.900
So music survives dislocation
and suburbanization

00:23:57.900 --> 00:24:00.260
when a subculture knows
what it wants

00:24:00.260 --> 00:24:02.020
from its school-trained musicians.

00:24:02.020 --> 00:24:04.290
And this is the part of
the story I'm telling.

00:24:04.290 --> 00:24:08.330
Education moved these kids off
the path to the assembly line,

00:24:08.330 --> 00:24:11.800
though some of them still had
to log time at factories to get

00:24:11.800 --> 00:24:14.720
by if the music work dried up.

00:24:14.720 --> 00:24:16.710
And various people
have told me that.

00:24:16.710 --> 00:24:20.920
One said, "Cass saved me from
the Detroit industrial ghetto."

00:24:20.920 --> 00:24:25.720 position:56%
Like [inaudible], an African
American violinist, was the only one

00:24:25.720 --> 00:24:29.250 position:56%
in the orchestra, and the first one
in some major orchestras in America,

00:24:29.250 --> 00:24:32.320
and he was glad to leave an
industrial future for a position

00:24:32.320 --> 00:24:34.130
in a major symphony orchestra.

00:24:34.130 --> 00:24:38.960
Most of these kids were immigrants
from Europe or the American South.

00:24:38.960 --> 00:24:43.370
The renowned violinist
sisters Ida and Ani Kavafian,

00:24:43.370 --> 00:24:48.180
standbys at Lincoln Center
music, were born in Istanbul.

00:24:48.180 --> 00:24:50.080
My successful buddies Daryl

00:24:50.080 --> 00:24:52.750 position:56%
and Robert Barnes [assumed spelling]
actually came from Kentucky.

00:24:52.750 --> 00:24:56.360 position:56%
And against the hillbilly stereotype
that you might have, their mother,

00:24:56.360 --> 00:24:59.310
who was from Lexington, was a
professional French horn player

00:24:59.310 --> 00:25:01.990
who was in the Detroit
symphony when she had to quit

00:25:01.990 --> 00:25:04.230
because she couldn't be a mom
and a professional in those days.

00:25:04.230 --> 00:25:06.960
And both those boys ended up
in the Philadelphia Orchestra

00:25:06.960 --> 00:25:09.390
and the Boston Symphony,
coming from Kentucky.

00:25:09.390 --> 00:25:14.730
Okay, so this nexus, this
convergence that happened say

00:25:14.730 --> 00:25:18.320
in classical music is something
that really, really interests me.

00:25:18.320 --> 00:25:24.750 position:56%
And my friend Rita Sloan [assumed
spelling] that I knew very well came

00:25:24.750 --> 00:25:29.240
as a refugee after the war, from
displaced person camps to Detroit.

00:25:29.240 --> 00:25:33.770
Her family decided they had to have
a piano, and gave it its own room

00:25:33.770 --> 00:25:36.590 position:56%
in their house, so she had to double
up with her sister [laughter].

00:25:36.590 --> 00:25:40.110
So this is the kind of
value systems that were --

00:25:40.110 --> 00:25:42.750
came with families that I'm
also very interested in.

00:25:42.750 --> 00:25:44.950
Okay, so now that brings
me to part three,

00:25:44.950 --> 00:25:47.610
more on the actual
internal subcultural space

00:25:47.610 --> 00:25:49.540
of these communities.

00:25:49.540 --> 00:25:52.940
So there are three books
that actually help me on it,

00:25:52.940 --> 00:25:55.040
because there is no literature
on the city of Detroit to read.

00:25:55.040 --> 00:25:59.330
I mean, anything about the city of
Detroit, sociology, urban history,

00:25:59.330 --> 00:26:02.300
there's like fewer than this
many books that are worth reading

00:26:02.300 --> 00:26:03.600
about the city of Detroit.

00:26:03.600 --> 00:26:05.850
Such a major place,
it's just unbelievable.

00:26:05.850 --> 00:26:09.580
And on music, fortunately in
recent years three books came out.

00:26:09.580 --> 00:26:13.500
One was called, "Before Motown,"
which is the history of jazz

00:26:13.500 --> 00:26:16.730
in Detroit, "Before
Motown," very, very helpful.

00:26:16.730 --> 00:26:19.720
There's one this -- Lori's
book on Polish American music,

00:26:19.720 --> 00:26:21.550
and one called "Detroit
Country Music"

00:26:21.550 --> 00:26:22.980
on the white Southern community.

00:26:22.980 --> 00:26:25.760
So this makes it possible for me
to do a little work that I'll lay

00:26:25.760 --> 00:26:27.940
out for you and make some maps.

00:26:27.940 --> 00:26:32.220
I had some GIS maps
made by students.

00:26:32.220 --> 00:26:37.020
And this is just I'm -- they're
not like statistically viable,

00:26:37.020 --> 00:26:39.420
but these books are
done by enthusiasts

00:26:39.420 --> 00:26:41.410
who tell you what club
everybody played in,

00:26:41.410 --> 00:26:42.710
and where the addresses were.

00:26:42.710 --> 00:26:44.010
I love books like this.

00:26:44.010 --> 00:26:47.950
And then you can actually use
them to construct some kind

00:26:47.950 --> 00:26:49.770
of geographic spatial sense.

00:26:49.770 --> 00:26:53.470
So I'll give you a
little bit of this.

00:26:53.470 --> 00:26:58.360
This is a map that combines
Polish versus country music.

00:26:58.360 --> 00:27:01.620
And you can see that the country
music is more the star-shaped

00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:04.380
things, and the Polish
music is more concentrated.

00:27:04.380 --> 00:27:07.310
And country music is
all over the city

00:27:07.310 --> 00:27:10.110
because there was this huge
scattered population where somebody

00:27:10.110 --> 00:27:13.360
