00:34:36.290 --> 00:34:38.850
Then at Cass Tech, right?

00:34:38.850 --> 00:34:40.150
Yeah, okay, now we go back.

00:34:40.150 --> 00:34:42.270
And that is the interior world.

00:34:42.270 --> 00:34:45.820
Okay, my parents' social circle
gathered at the orchestra concerts,

00:34:45.820 --> 00:34:49.590
and the Jewish community kept the
Detroit Symphony Orchestra alive

00:34:49.590 --> 00:34:51.090
when the flickering interest

00:34:51.090 --> 00:34:54.230
of the city's auto moguls
endangered the organization.

00:34:54.230 --> 00:34:55.820
They came to this late.

00:34:55.820 --> 00:34:57.120
It's Detroit.

00:34:57.120 --> 00:34:58.420
It's not Chicago and
Cleveland, you know.

00:34:58.420 --> 00:34:59.720
There was no orchestra hall.

00:34:59.720 --> 00:35:01.020
They -- I mean, that's
another story.

00:35:01.020 --> 00:35:02.890
If I had time I would tell
you, which is very amusing.

00:35:02.890 --> 00:35:05.670
And they get this, but they
like pull their money out of it.

00:35:05.670 --> 00:35:07.200
So the Jews wanted it to happen.

00:35:07.200 --> 00:35:10.740
A couple of people, including
two of my violin teachers,

00:35:10.740 --> 00:35:12.320
organized a chamber symphony --

00:35:12.320 --> 00:35:15.370
a chamber orchestra
called the Little Symphony

00:35:15.370 --> 00:35:16.670
that kept things running.

00:35:16.670 --> 00:35:20.440
They gave concerts at an
upscale Jewish restaurant

00:35:20.440 --> 00:35:22.280
when there was no Detroit Symphony.

00:35:22.280 --> 00:35:26.760
At another time a guy called
Sams Cutright kept sponsorship

00:35:26.760 --> 00:35:28.060
of the symphony going.

00:35:28.060 --> 00:35:32.430
Community ladies had organized
the Music Study Club in the 1920s,

00:35:32.430 --> 00:35:35.210
which paralleled the
non-Jewish Tuesday Musicale

00:35:35.210 --> 00:35:36.990
that went back to the 1880s.

00:35:36.990 --> 00:35:38.290
And I was in that crowd.

00:35:38.290 --> 00:35:40.100
We played at Music
Study Club gatherings,

00:35:40.100 --> 00:35:42.890
and they gave scholarships
for child prodigies

00:35:42.890 --> 00:35:45.460
who went off to have big careers.

00:35:45.460 --> 00:35:49.310
One of the interesting moments was
the decision to hire a classical --

00:35:49.310 --> 00:35:52.450
a Jewish composer from Vienna
named Julius [inaudible]

00:35:52.450 --> 00:35:56.370
who was charged with, in 1940,

00:35:56.370 --> 00:35:59.000
to organize a professional-level
orchestra and a music school

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:01.570
at the Jewish Community
Center, which was very linked

00:36:01.570 --> 00:36:03.200
to Detroit Symphony Orchestra.

00:36:03.200 --> 00:36:07.280
So there's this parallel
establishment and integration

00:36:07.280 --> 00:36:11.370
of the Jewish community with the
mainstream community at this level.

00:36:11.370 --> 00:36:15.460 position:56%
He's also bringing in -- he had
lived in Palestine, so he's bringing

00:36:15.460 --> 00:36:19.380
in Palestine sound and Zionist
things in his own compositions.

00:36:19.380 --> 00:36:22.670 position:56%
He gets the Detroit Symphony
Orchestra to do a Jewish Music Week.

00:36:22.670 --> 00:36:23.970
Very complicated.

00:36:23.970 --> 00:36:25.270
They're playing in black churches.

00:36:25.270 --> 00:36:26.900
There's a lot of outreach.

00:36:26.900 --> 00:36:28.830
He couldn't control everything.

00:36:28.830 --> 00:36:31.830
As I was looking through the
newspaper, the Detroit Jewish News,

00:36:31.830 --> 00:36:35.770
1942, [inaudible] is giving a
concert with a black church.

00:36:35.770 --> 00:36:37.470
And on the same page it's announced

00:36:37.470 --> 00:36:41.850
that the Jewish Center cub pack
will be putting on a minstrel show.

00:36:41.850 --> 00:36:44.920
So [laughter] it's a
rather complicated set

00:36:44.920 --> 00:36:50.300
of relationships say in 1942.

00:36:50.300 --> 00:36:54.000
So this epitomizes the
dynamism, the complexity

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:57.600
of American Jewish musical life
that look both outward and inward

00:36:57.600 --> 00:37:01.090
in a turbulent century that saw
the restriction of immigration,

00:37:01.090 --> 00:37:03.380
the Holocaust, establishment
of the State of Israel.

00:37:03.380 --> 00:37:07.420
But Detroit was the most
anti-Semitic city in America.

00:37:07.420 --> 00:37:12.060
Henry Ford funded vicious
propaganda, and the publication

00:37:12.060 --> 00:37:15.420
of the elders -- protocol
of the Elders of Zion.

00:37:15.420 --> 00:37:17.650
The radio priest Father
Coughlin was [inaudible]

00:37:17.650 --> 00:37:21.110
against the Jews every week
to millions across America.

00:37:21.110 --> 00:37:24.640
Three was a plot by the
Michigan Black Legion

00:37:24.640 --> 00:37:27.620
to murder a million Jews by
planting bombs in every synagogue

00:37:27.620 --> 00:37:29.850
across America on Yom Kippur.

00:37:29.850 --> 00:37:32.650
Okay, so I'm learning what
my parents were living

00:37:32.650 --> 00:37:37.350
through in this city
in their cultural life.

00:37:37.350 --> 00:37:39.980
But they also kept their
traditional channels

00:37:39.980 --> 00:37:41.680
of music, and that was that photo.

00:37:41.680 --> 00:37:45.730
Here I am, my father's teaching me
how to do my bar mitzvah chanting.

00:37:45.730 --> 00:37:49.790
And I had a really
interesting experience

00:37:49.790 --> 00:37:51.540
of a grad student named
Garrett Field,

00:37:51.540 --> 00:37:53.460
who was a specialist
in South Asian music.

00:37:53.460 --> 00:37:56.700
And he said, "I want to do a
paper on" -- I said, "On what?"

00:37:56.700 --> 00:38:00.050
He said, "I want to talk about this
synagogue boys' choir I was in."

00:38:00.050 --> 00:38:02.560
I said -- I had no idea
he was even Jewish.

00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:03.860
I said, "Where was that?"

00:38:03.860 --> 00:38:05.160
And he said, "Detroit."

00:38:05.160 --> 00:38:06.460
I said, "What synagogue?"

00:38:06.460 --> 00:38:09.330
He said, "B'nai Moshe," which
is where I was bar mitzvah.

00:38:09.330 --> 00:38:11.640 position:56%
And I said, "Sure," you know, right.

00:38:11.640 --> 00:38:15.030
So he and his brother
were deeply affected

00:38:15.030 --> 00:38:18.070
by the Cantor there
named Cantor Louis Klein.

00:38:18.070 --> 00:38:19.540
One of my [inaudible]
was the history

00:38:19.540 --> 00:38:21.710
of the American Cantorate
that I did.

00:38:21.710 --> 00:38:23.580
And Louis Klein actually
was a contributor

00:38:23.580 --> 00:38:25.490
to that project, so
I knew who he was.

00:38:25.490 --> 00:38:26.790
He was another immigrant.

00:38:26.790 --> 00:38:29.380
He grew up in Romania.

00:38:29.380 --> 00:38:31.570
He came by Belgium and London.

00:38:31.570 --> 00:38:35.680
And in Detroit he sang,
you know, on Radio and TV.

00:38:35.680 --> 00:38:37.760
He'd concert at Catholic retreats.

00:38:37.760 --> 00:38:39.730
He was another one
of these immigrants

00:38:39.730 --> 00:38:41.860
like [inaudible] who
he was musicality.

00:38:41.860 --> 00:38:46.500
But he's using it in the system
of ancient Hebrew sacred music.

00:38:46.500 --> 00:38:50.310
So I'll read you two little
quotes from the Field brothers

00:38:50.310 --> 00:38:53.780
about the experience
of being in the choir.

00:38:53.780 --> 00:38:57.280
"As a young boy raised in a
conservative Jewish family,

00:38:57.280 --> 00:39:00.480
I could sense the High
Holidays just around the corner.

00:39:00.480 --> 00:39:02.800
The air became cooler, and
the leaves began to color.

00:39:02.800 --> 00:39:05.990
Soon I would be on the bimah,"
the platform of the synagogue,

00:39:05.990 --> 00:39:09.760
"with my boys' choir cohorts,
circled around the [speaking

00:39:09.760 --> 00:39:12.210
in foreign language] on the table
on which the Torah scroll sits,

00:39:12.210 --> 00:39:15.020
accompanied by the
hazzan Louis Klein."

00:39:15.020 --> 00:39:17.040
The other one says, "I
remember the excitement

00:39:17.040 --> 00:39:19.820
and nervousness before
heading onstage when we sat

00:39:19.820 --> 00:39:23.790
with our families, like secretive
spies with alternate identities.

00:39:23.790 --> 00:39:27.120
One second the humble and
anonymous son of the Field family,

00:39:27.120 --> 00:39:30.650
and a minute later, zam!, a
regular mini-Cantor belting

00:39:30.650 --> 00:39:33.590
out sonorous renditions of
traditional Jewish songs

00:39:33.590 --> 00:39:35.920
for the audience of
fellow congregants.

00:39:35.920 --> 00:39:38.330
We had done something great,
and exciting, and memorable.

00:39:38.330 --> 00:39:41.540
It was like a secret proud
friendship and comradeship."

00:39:41.540 --> 00:39:43.520
So this is a really
wonderful statement

00:39:43.520 --> 00:39:46.960
about an internal subcultural life
at the same time that they're doing

00:39:46.960 --> 00:39:49.240
as much outreach as they can.

00:39:49.240 --> 00:39:52.600 position:56%
So I'm going to close here with part
four here, some little reflections

00:39:52.600 --> 00:39:56.790
on the notion of urban spatiality
and music, and the relationships

00:39:56.790 --> 00:40:00.760
of all these, because I'm, you
know, mapping out this vast area,

00:40:00.760 --> 00:40:05.470
and I'm trying to find some
kinds of ways of doing that.

00:40:05.470 --> 00:40:08.720
Before the Internet,
then, a large urban area

00:40:08.720 --> 00:40:12.020
like Detroit was a fairly bounded
system, even if it was plugged

00:40:12.020 --> 00:40:18.880 position:56%
into like national and international
circuits of family and marketing.

00:40:18.880 --> 00:40:21.810
And Lefebvre talks about
the imagined space,

00:40:21.810 --> 00:40:24.010
which is the imagined
idea of the city,

00:40:24.010 --> 00:40:26.170
the designed space,
and the lived space.

00:40:26.170 --> 00:40:29.220
And this plurality
co-existence and simultaneity.

00:40:29.220 --> 00:40:31.560
Music operates among
all these world.

00:40:31.560 --> 00:40:34.260
It's -- it flows into
all kinds of channels.

00:40:34.260 --> 00:40:38.900
So I'm just going to give you two
little moments that suggest the --

00:40:38.900 --> 00:40:43.090
what I find the interesting
issues around some of this,

00:40:43.090 --> 00:40:45.340
using Yusef Lateef, who was one

00:40:45.340 --> 00:40:47.920
of the most influential
musical Detroiters.

00:40:47.920 --> 00:40:51.840
In the mid-'50s, Lateef was
drawn to Islam at a time

00:40:51.840 --> 00:40:55.510
