because of Islamic connections.

00:41:06.970 --> 00:41:08.580
And he was" -- but no.

00:41:08.580 --> 00:41:11.040
It was an Arab American
coworker on the line

00:41:11.040 --> 00:41:13.840
at the Chrysler factory, okay.

00:41:13.840 --> 00:41:17.450
Now this is a real Detroit story,
then speaking of the comradery

00:41:17.450 --> 00:41:20.450
of the polyglot workforce
of the auto industry.

00:41:20.450 --> 00:41:22.400
For Lateef the rebab was different

00:41:22.400 --> 00:41:26.020
from what I'm calling
inherently-available resources

00:41:26.020 --> 00:41:27.320
he had.

00:41:27.320 --> 00:41:28.770
This is what you grow up with
and what you have available,

00:41:28.770 --> 00:41:31.570
what you have in the family,
and what you get in school.

00:41:31.570 --> 00:41:34.340
These are things that are
inherently available to you.

00:41:34.340 --> 00:41:36.090
But then there are other things

00:41:36.090 --> 00:41:38.950
which I'm calling adjacent
resources.

00:41:38.950 --> 00:41:42.300
The factory allowed for
the nearness of a music

00:41:42.300 --> 00:41:46.970 position:56%
that might have been the third
category, my inaccessible resources.

00:41:46.970 --> 00:41:48.370
So there are adjacent resources --

00:41:48.370 --> 00:41:52.180
inherent ones, adjacent ones that
are around there that you might run

00:41:52.180 --> 00:41:53.710
into and use, and ones that are

00:41:53.710 --> 00:41:57.030
for whatever reason simply
not accessible to you at all,

00:41:57.030 --> 00:41:58.790
physically or conceptually.

00:41:58.790 --> 00:42:03.270
This reminds me -- his experience
reminds me in a passage in a poem

00:42:03.270 --> 00:42:07.190
by Philip Levine, which was the
great American poet from Detroit.

00:42:07.190 --> 00:42:09.630
And I'm using poetry, and
literature, and other things

00:42:09.630 --> 00:42:12.360
to try to flesh this out.

00:42:12.360 --> 00:42:15.980
He happened to have to work on
the assembly line a little bit,

00:42:15.980 --> 00:42:19.780
and he writes about, "My
friend Marion, the ex-junkie

00:42:19.780 --> 00:42:25.050 position:56%
and novice drop-forge worker, off
by himself, humming "Body and Soul."

00:42:25.050 --> 00:42:27.720
He played with Hawkins
before his troubles,

00:42:27.720 --> 00:42:31.250
and now has four 10-inch
bluebirds left to prove it."

00:42:31.250 --> 00:42:34.640
Hawkins here is Coleman
Hawkins, a major figure.

00:42:34.640 --> 00:42:37.020
And the bluebirds are these
records that you've got over here.

00:42:37.020 --> 00:42:38.800
It's a famous jazz record label.

00:42:38.800 --> 00:42:42.490
So the adjacency of the workplace
gives Philip Levine access

00:42:42.490 --> 00:42:45.730
to a friend of his who used
to play with Coleman Hawkins.

00:42:45.730 --> 00:42:48.480
So it's something like
that Lateef story.

00:42:48.480 --> 00:42:53.110
The second one is about me
and Lateef in a funny way.

00:42:53.110 --> 00:42:57.790
At the end of the '50s I used to
clutch my violin case at 6:45 a.m.

00:42:57.790 --> 00:43:01.430
on a cold corner to catch the
Dexter bus down to Cass Tech

00:43:01.430 --> 00:43:03.500
to get there for orchestra
rehearsal.

00:43:03.500 --> 00:43:06.100
After white flight I was
living in a neighborhood

00:43:06.100 --> 00:43:09.370
that by then had only
7% of Detroit's Jews,

00:43:09.370 --> 00:43:11.700
and everybody else
was African American.

00:43:11.700 --> 00:43:16.410
And I would see this club with
a glass front you looked in.

00:43:16.410 --> 00:43:18.060
It was called the Minor Key.

00:43:18.060 --> 00:43:19.580
And there would be
hand-lettered signs

00:43:19.580 --> 00:43:21.990
in the window saying
Yusef Lateef, you know,

00:43:21.990 --> 00:43:23.290
John Coltrane, or whatever.

00:43:23.290 --> 00:43:25.660
And in fact, I've checked.

00:43:25.660 --> 00:43:27.650
Yes, Lateef played
the Minor Key then,

00:43:27.650 --> 00:43:30.770
exactly when I would
have been standing there.

00:43:30.770 --> 00:43:34.100
Because -- so this was
adjacent physically to me,

00:43:34.100 --> 00:43:37.000
but the Minor Key was not
available to me conceptually

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:41.770
because I had all this
inherently-available music starting

00:43:41.770 --> 00:43:45.380
with Russian songs, Gilbert and
Sullivan, many things that I had

00:43:45.380 --> 00:43:49.110
in classical music which were
physically extremely far away,

00:43:49.110 --> 00:43:52.040
but conceptually inherent
and close to me.

00:43:52.040 --> 00:43:53.850
But here was this thing
that was physically close

00:43:53.850 --> 00:43:55.570
which was conceptually distant.

00:43:55.570 --> 00:43:58.260
It never occurred to me to
step inside to hear the music,

00:43:58.260 --> 00:44:00.460
so I missed all of the
Golden Age of jazz.

00:44:00.460 --> 00:44:01.940
And I know other kids --

00:44:01.940 --> 00:44:04.340
I've mentioned this to kids
that went to school with me.

00:44:04.340 --> 00:44:05.990
And they said, "Oh, we just to
