and she loved the music in Detroit

00:45:46.350 --> 00:45:49.110
and talked about the great
Emancipation Day concerts,

00:45:49.110 --> 00:45:52.780
which I had never heard of
and never would have gone to.

00:45:52.780 --> 00:45:56.610
That is what I would call an
inaccessible resource to me,

00:45:56.610 --> 00:45:59.650
even though for her it was
something really important

00:45:59.650 --> 00:46:00.950
that happened every year.

00:46:00.950 --> 00:46:02.830
Okay, so -- and of course,

00:46:02.830 --> 00:46:07.610
many African Americans had many
experiences with inaccessibility

00:46:07.610 --> 00:46:10.140
because of conditions
of American life,

00:46:10.140 --> 00:46:12.320
including in the musical realm.

00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:14.730
So that's part of this complexity.

00:46:14.730 --> 00:46:17.370
So cities offer conceptual spaces

00:46:17.370 --> 00:46:19.700
and concrete sites,
but not neutrally.

00:46:19.700 --> 00:46:22.680
It's not just the designed
city of the street grid.

00:46:22.680 --> 00:46:25.260
In Detroit all the players,
individuals, groups,

00:46:25.260 --> 00:46:28.230
the establishment, created and
pushed the limits of availability,

00:46:28.230 --> 00:46:30.750
physically and imaginatively.

00:46:30.750 --> 00:46:34.800
Music could be heard or
unheard, mandated or without,

00:46:34.800 --> 00:46:36.650
like the instruments from Miller,

00:46:36.650 --> 00:46:40.690
according to largely unwritten
rules of improvisation.

00:46:40.690 --> 00:46:43.240
Collaboration and separation
coexisted

00:46:43.240 --> 00:46:46.790
in a constantly-shifting
landscape within a community,

00:46:46.790 --> 00:46:49.650 position:56%
between neighborhoods, and citywide.

00:46:49.650 --> 00:46:52.830
And Detroit is, of course,
famous for its mobility, created

00:46:52.830 --> 00:46:56.620
and promoted by a capitalist
drive that people had to work

00:46:56.620 --> 00:46:59.730
