00:47:42.960 --> 00:47:45.100
But I'm trying to show the richness

00:47:45.100 --> 00:47:49.380
of exploring the inner musical
workings of an American city not

00:47:49.380 --> 00:47:52.670
yet exploded by white flight
and the triumph of the freeway.

00:47:52.670 --> 00:47:55.590
The last phase of the
dominance of the Northeast

00:47:55.590 --> 00:47:58.830
of an almost desperate style of
social and industrial engineering

00:47:58.830 --> 00:48:01.890
and intense, close-up
interaction of an older collection

00:48:01.890 --> 00:48:05.710
of American subcultures
with modernity.

00:48:05.710 --> 00:48:09.490
It's a good site for spatiality
studies because it's so tight.

00:48:09.490 --> 00:48:13.090
It's 1910, and by 1970 it's over.

00:48:13.090 --> 00:48:16.020
When Detroit was a byword
for power, not ruin.

00:48:16.020 --> 00:48:20.050
And for their manic musical
momentum that we all know

00:48:20.050 --> 00:48:22.270
of because we all hear
Motown songs like every day.

00:48:22.270 --> 00:48:25.520
So we were the first to
see the new model cars

00:48:25.520 --> 00:48:28.120
