which paralleled as
an industrial system,

00:53:26.080 --> 00:53:29.020
was paralleling the auto
industry very directly.

00:53:29.020 --> 00:53:31.400
That's a real Detroit story.

00:53:31.400 --> 00:53:34.670
And that part of it appeals to me.

00:53:34.670 --> 00:53:37.440
&gt;&gt; There's another
thing that interests me.

00:53:37.440 --> 00:53:39.230
I grew up in Birmingham, and you --

00:53:39.230 --> 00:53:40.530
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: Yeah,
yeah, yeah, right.

00:53:40.530 --> 00:53:42.400
&gt;&gt; -- had to take the
Greyhound bus downtown just

00:53:42.400 --> 00:53:45.110
to watch a couple movies or
watch Louis Armstrong onstage.

00:53:45.110 --> 00:53:46.410
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: Well, there you go.

00:53:46.410 --> 00:53:49.240
You're another one of
those, right, yeah.

00:53:49.240 --> 00:53:53.120
&gt;&gt; [Inaudible] a lot of the clubs,
French, the Flame, a whole bunch --

00:53:53.120 --> 00:53:54.420
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: Great, yeah.

00:53:54.420 --> 00:53:55.720
These were the -- yeah, these
were the major -- right.

00:53:55.720 --> 00:53:57.210
&gt;&gt; But you know, one thing
that happened, it seems to me,

00:53:57.210 --> 00:53:59.370 position:56%
that I was told by my friend from --

00:53:59.370 --> 00:54:03.570
67, it was the dividing line
of being able to go to clubs.

00:54:03.570 --> 00:54:08.500
And black friends of my
general economic background,

00:54:08.500 --> 00:54:11.520
they said for them it was not
welcoming to go to the clubs

00:54:11.520 --> 00:54:15.210
that we always used to go
to as a shared experience.

00:54:15.210 --> 00:54:16.510
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: Oh, okay.

00:54:16.510 --> 00:54:17.810
&gt;&gt; But the riots --

00:54:17.810 --> 00:54:19.110
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: But they weren't
welcome in the white clubs?

00:54:19.110 --> 00:54:20.410
&gt;&gt; There were welcome.

00:54:20.410 --> 00:54:21.710
They didn't feel welcome
in the black clubs.

00:54:21.710 --> 00:54:23.010
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: In the black clubs?

00:54:23.010 --> 00:54:24.310
Oh, the white people didn't feel --

00:54:24.310 --> 00:54:26.610
&gt;&gt; No, I'm talking about
black middle-class --

00:54:26.610 --> 00:54:27.910
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: Oh, all right.

00:54:27.910 --> 00:54:29.210
&gt;&gt; -- black.

00:54:29.210 --> 00:54:30.510
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: I see.

00:54:30.510 --> 00:54:31.810
Yeah.

00:54:31.810 --> 00:54:33.110
&gt;&gt; Felt that they weren't welcome
as much in the black clubs.

00:54:33.110 --> 00:54:37.560
I thought that was a watershed on
some [inaudible] back in a while.

00:54:37.560 --> 00:54:41.080
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: Well, there still
are some clubs, but you know,

00:54:41.080 --> 00:54:43.540
I mean, the whole thing was gutted.

00:54:43.540 --> 00:54:44.960
I mean, Hastings Street was the --

00:54:44.960 --> 00:54:48.490
was literally paved over to
create the Chrysler Freeway.

00:54:48.490 --> 00:54:51.140
So they destroyed the entire
culture of this population

00:54:51.140 --> 00:54:52.690
and their music community.

00:54:52.690 --> 00:54:55.780
They literally just did that.

00:54:55.780 --> 00:54:59.410
So you know, that offers
you fewer choices, right?

00:54:59.410 --> 00:55:00.710
&gt;&gt; No question.

00:55:00.710 --> 00:55:02.010
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: Yeah?

00:55:02.010 --> 00:55:04.510
&gt;&gt; As a native Kentuckian
I was kind of taken aback

00:55:04.510 --> 00:55:08.520
when you said [inaudible] actually
a French horn player from --

00:55:08.520 --> 00:55:12.100 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: No, because of the
-- right, because of the stereotypes

00:55:12.100 --> 00:55:13.900
&gt;&gt; -- that Kentucky
is all hillbillies.

00:55:13.900 --> 00:55:18.010
You may as well say Michigan
is all industrial ghetto.

00:55:18.010 --> 00:55:19.310
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: Yeah, no.

00:55:19.310 --> 00:55:20.610
That's why I used the
example, because it goes

00:55:20.610 --> 00:55:22.860
against these stereotypes
that people have

00:55:22.860 --> 00:55:26.690 position:56%
about who these people were and what
they might have been listening to.

00:55:26.690 --> 00:55:30.450
No, I mean, that's exactly
why I brought that example.

00:55:32.070 --> 00:55:33.490 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Can you tell us a little bit more

00:55:33.490 --> 00:55:37.400
about the ethnic music
like the polka?

00:55:37.400 --> 00:55:43.050
&gt;&gt; Mark Slobin: Yeah, the -- oh,
it's fascinating, this whole world.

00:55:43.050 --> 00:55:46.390
There are different
stories to tell, you know,

00:55:46.390 --> 00:55:51.490
depending on which group it is
and how musically active they were

00:55:51.490 --> 00:55:55.350 position:56%
for their size and scale I mean,
I've been trying to figure that out.

00:55:55.350 --> 00:55:57.740
So I have some stories of
some of the communities.

00:55:57.740 --> 00:56:00.060
And I know -- and some of
them interact with each other.

00:56:00.060 --> 00:56:02.420
Others really kept to themselves.

00:56:02.420 --> 00:56:07.040
The Poles were so massive,
this 350,000 people population

00:56:07.040 --> 00:56:10.420
in this city, that
they didn't need --

00:56:10.420 --> 00:56:12.980
you know, they were really
self-sufficient in a way.

00:56:12.980 --> 00:56:15.530
So it's -- a lot of people
played with Poles, and --

00:56:15.530 --> 00:56:18.640
but they didn't have to
kind of go out that much

00:56:18.640 --> 00:56:19.960
in certain kinds of ways.

00:56:19.960 --> 00:56:23.590
But they benefitted from the
school systems, yeah, and the --

00:56:23.590 --> 00:56:26.910
some of them went off
on this jazz track.

00:56:26.910 --> 00:56:30.470
Where smaller groups, the
Serbs, and the Croats,

00:56:30.470 --> 00:56:34.000
and the Romanians would play
together and share repertoires,

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:38.430
but then you know, later when
you've got the Yugoslavia war,

00:56:38.430 --> 00:56:39.730
this -- that stopped.

00:56:39.730 --> 00:56:44.250
You know, so these diasporic
lives connect to homelands

00:56:44.250 --> 00:56:47.510
and what's going on in other
places in certain ways.

00:56:47.510 --> 00:56:50.280
There were gypsy, roaming
musicians who moved

00:56:50.280 --> 00:56:53.320
around from one thing to another.

00:56:53.320 --> 00:56:57.610
It's complicated, and it's
just really badly researched.

00:56:57.610 --> 00:57:02.120
There's just very little that
I've been able to, you know,

00:57:02.120 --> 00:57:05.730
bring into this to really do
a thorough job, which would --

00:57:05.730 --> 00:57:08.410 position:56%
nobody kept records of these people.

00:57:08.410 --> 00:57:10.850
So you can talk to some of them,
and there's some things to read.

00:57:10.850 --> 00:57:14.200
But -- I mean, some
interviews and things like that.

00:57:14.200 --> 00:57:16.910
But there's not anywhere
the kind of data you'd want

00:57:16.910 --> 00:57:21.220
to have a really serious mapping
of what all those people were

00:57:21.220 --> 00:57:24.310
up to, those communities.

